Iast February...

24
00:02:22,589 --> 00:02:25,581
I was reading a story to
my advanced writer's workshop...

25
00:02:25,659 --> 00:02:28,719
by one James Leer,
junior Lit major...

26
00:02:28,795 --> 00:02:32,060
and sole inhabitant
of his own gloomy gulag.

27
00:02:32,132 --> 00:02:34,293
"She bit the flesh of her lip...

28
00:02:34,368 --> 00:02:37,064
closed her eyes, mute."

29
00:02:41,141 --> 00:02:45,544
[Narrating]James' stories were
about as sunny as his disposition.

30
00:02:45,612 --> 00:02:47,773
I was distracted.

31
00:02:47,848 --> 00:02:49,907
Maybe it had something to do
with the fact...

32
00:02:49,983 --> 00:02:51,974
that my wife
had left me that morning.

33
00:02:52,052 --> 00:02:53,815
So. Anyone?

34
00:02:53,887 --> 00:02:56,253
Maybe not.
Wives had left me before.

35
00:02:56,323 --> 00:02:59,918
- Carrie.
-As usual, James' classmates...

36
00:02:59,993 --> 00:03:02,223
aware of a writer's
inherent vulnerability...

37
00:03:02,296 --> 00:03:06,232
offered their sensitive,
gentle opinions.

38
00:03:06,300 --> 00:03:09,201
I mean, Jesus,
what is it with you Catholics?

39
00:03:09,269 --> 00:03:12,397
- [ Laughing ]
- All right. All right.

40
00:03:12,472 --> 00:03:14,906
Let's try to be
constructive here, shall we?

41
00:03:16,610 --> 00:03:18,544
Howard , what about you?

42
00:03:18,612 --> 00:03:20,546
- I hated it.
- [Laughter]

43
00:03:20,614 --> 00:03:22,844
His stories make me
want to kill myself.

44
00:03:24,851 --> 00:03:27,786
That's not exactly what I meant
by being constructive, Howard .

45
00:03:31,158 --> 00:03:34,059
Yes, Hannah?

46
00:03:34,127 --> 00:03:36,118
I think maybe we're
missing the point.

47
00:03:36,196 --> 00:03:37,720
[Narrating]
Hannah Green.

48
00:03:37,798 --> 00:03:40,130
A talented writer who
rented a room in my house.

49
00:03:40,200 --> 00:03:43,328
I knew her to be
insightful, kind...

50
00:03:43,403 --> 00:03:46,463
and compulsively clad
in red cowboy boots.

51
00:03:46,540 --> 00:03:49,100
I had, in fact, never once
seen her without them.

52
00:03:49,176 --> 00:03:53,545
He respects us enough to forget us,
and... that takes courage.

53
00:03:53,613 --> 00:03:57,549
Well put, Hannah. And a good note
to end on, I think.

54
00:03:57,617 --> 00:04:01,280
Oh, don 't forget about
WordFest this weekend.

55
00:04:01,355 --> 00:04:02,982
And those of you who are
driving V.I.P.s...

56
00:04:03,056 --> 00:04:04,421
to the
cocktail party this evening...

57
00:04:04,491 --> 00:04:06,652
should have them
at the chancellor's house...

58
00:04:06,727 --> 00:04:08,319
no later than 5:30.

59
00:04:08,395 --> 00:04:11,489
[ Chattering ]

60
00:04:11,565 --> 00:04:14,329
Thank you for that.
Is he all right?

61
00:04:17,471 --> 00:04:20,531
I think so.
How about you?

62
00:04:20,607 --> 00:04:22,768
Me? Yeah. Why?

63
00:04:24,044 --> 00:04:25,978
Just checking.

64
00:04:30,584 --> 00:04:33,519
[James]
Turn off the light, please.

65
00:04:41,361 --> 00:04:43,852
[Narrating]
It felt good to be in the car.

66
00:04:43,930 --> 00:04:46,728
Alone.
Where I could clear my head.

67
00:04:51,905 --> 00:04:54,135
Tonight was
the opening of WordFest...

68
00:04:54,207 --> 00:04:56,732
the university's annual
three-day "gabathon "...

69
00:04:56,810 --> 00:04:58,710
for writers and wanna-bes.

70
00:04:58,779 --> 00:05:02,613
My editor, Terry Crabtree,
was flying in for the event.

71
00:05:02,682 --> 00:05:06,641
He alone had championed my
last novel, Arsonist's Daughter...

72
00:05:06,720 --> 00:05:09,450
and its critical success
had put us both on the map.

73
00:05:09,523 --> 00:05:11,718
But that was seven years ago...

74
00:05:11,792 --> 00:05:14,727
and I still hadn't
finished my follow-up.

75
00:05:14,795 --> 00:05:17,263
I knew Terry didn't give
a rat's ass about WordFest.

76
00:05:17,330 --> 00:05:20,561
He was coming to town to get
a look at my long-overdue book.

77
00:05:22,102 --> 00:05:25,162
I had to keep him at bay.

78
00:05:27,974 --> 00:05:31,171
-Ah, Tripp.
-Crabtree, how are you, my friend?

79
00:05:31,244 --> 00:05:34,338
- It's good to see you, Tripp.
- Let me help you with this.

80
00:05:34,414 --> 00:05:36,644
Say hello to my new friend.

81
00:05:36,716 --> 00:05:39,048
- Miss Antonia--
- Sloviak.

82
00:05:39,119 --> 00:05:41,986
Nice to meet you.
This way.

83
00:05:42,055 --> 00:05:44,523
I took the liberty of inviting
Antonia to tonight's festivities.

84
00:05:44,591 --> 00:05:46,081
The more the merrier.

85
00:05:46,159 --> 00:05:48,184
Terry was telling me
about you on the plane.

86
00:05:48,261 --> 00:05:49,694
It was all so interesting.

87
00:05:49,763 --> 00:05:51,754
I was just explaining how
a book comes to be published...

88
00:05:51,832 --> 00:05:54,096
what you do as a writer,
what I do as an editor.

89
00:05:54,167 --> 00:05:58,331
I sweat blood for five years,
and he corrects my spelling.

90
00:05:58,405 --> 00:06:02,068
- That's exactly what he said.
- We know each other pretty well.

91
00:06:02,142 --> 00:06:05,509
And actually,
it's seven years.

92
00:06:05,579 --> 00:06:08,070
You know how many times I've
board ed an airplane just praying...

93
00:06:08,148 --> 00:06:11,345
that some gal like her would be
sitting down beside me?

94
00:06:11,418 --> 00:06:13,579
- She's a transvestite.
- You're stoned.

95
00:06:13,653 --> 00:06:16,952
- She's still a transvestite.
- So, how's the book?

96
00:06:17,023 --> 00:06:20,481
Uh, it's fine.
It's done.

97
00:06:20,560 --> 00:06:24,360
Basically. I got a little tinkering
I've still got to do.

98
00:06:24,431 --> 00:06:25,762
Great!

99
00:06:25,832 --> 00:06:28,062
I was hoping I could get a look
at it sometime over the weekend.

100
00:06:28,134 --> 00:06:30,830
It's gonna be a little tough. I'm
at a critical juncture right now.

101
00:06:30,904 --> 00:06:33,099
I thought you were
just tinkering.

102
00:06:33,173 --> 00:06:36,768
W-Well, I am, but I have little
details I've got to work on.

103
00:06:36,843 --> 00:06:38,902
I'm not gonna pressure you.
I just got off the plane.

104
00:06:38,979 --> 00:06:41,379
I mean, I get pressure.
You know? I get--

105
00:06:41,448 --> 00:06:44,474
Know what I mean?

106
00:06:44,551 --> 00:06:48,385
What the hell in the hootenanny
do you suppose that would be?

107
00:06:48,455 --> 00:06:51,049
[ Tripp ]
That would be a tuba.

108
00:06:55,028 --> 00:06:57,724
[ Terry] You didn't actually
purchase this car, did you?

109
00:06:57,797 --> 00:07:01,130
No, I got it from Jerry Nathan.
He owed me some money.

110
00:07:01,201 --> 00:07:03,192
Ah! He owes God money.

111
00:07:03,270 --> 00:07:05,761
Including my commission
on that faux novel of his.

112
00:07:05,839 --> 00:07:07,329
That perfume you're wearing,
Antonia...

113
00:07:07,407 --> 00:07:09,307
that wouldn't happen
to be Cristalle, would it?

114
00:07:09,376 --> 00:07:11,674
Um, uh, yes, it is.

115
00:07:11,745 --> 00:07:14,612
- How did you know?
- Lucky guess.

116
00:07:15,882 --> 00:07:17,816
[ Tripp Narrating]
The WordFest kickoff party...

117
00:07:17,884 --> 00:07:20,910
was always held at
Sara and Walter Gaskell's house.

118
00:07:20,987 --> 00:07:24,889
She was the chancellor, which
meant she oversaw the university.

119
00:07:24,958 --> 00:07:26,892
Her husband, Dr. Gaskell...

120
00:07:26,960 --> 00:07:28,894
was the chairman
of the English Department...

121
00:07:28,962 --> 00:07:31,453
which meant he oversaw me.

122
00:07:35,435 --> 00:07:37,528
Isn't that a nice greenhouse?

123
00:07:37,604 --> 00:07:40,095
It's Mrs. Gaskell's.
It's her hobby.

124
00:07:40,173 --> 00:07:42,164
[ Terry ] I thought you were
Mrs. Gaskell's hobby.

125
00:07:42,242 --> 00:07:45,211
Piss off, will you, Crabs?
I lost a wife today.

126
00:07:45,278 --> 00:07:50,545
You'll find another. She'll be
young, beautiful. They always are.

127
00:07:54,955 --> 00:07:57,856
Oh, hello, everyone.
Terry, good to see you again.

128
00:07:57,924 --> 00:08:01,018
Chancellor.
Don't you look ravishing.

129
00:08:02,762 --> 00:08:06,289
-Oh, oh. Easy.
-[ Chuckling ] I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

130
00:08:06,366 --> 00:08:07,355
It's these goddamn shoes.

131
00:08:07,434 --> 00:08:09,334
I don't know how anyone
can walk in these things.

132
00:08:09,402 --> 00:08:12,371
Practice.

133
00:08:12,439 --> 00:08:15,636
- I don't believe we've met.
- Antonia Sloviak.

134
00:08:15,709 --> 00:08:18,405
- [Dog Growling]
- Poe.

135
00:08:18,478 --> 00:08:21,038
- [ Barking ]
- Poe! Poe!

136
00:08:21,114 --> 00:08:23,048
Poe, stop! Poe!

137
00:08:23,116 --> 00:08:25,175
That wouldn't be
Walter's dog, would it?

138
00:08:25,251 --> 00:08:28,379
- Poe!
- Who's he barking at now?

139
00:08:28,455 --> 00:08:30,855
He 's still barking at me.
He 's blind.

140
00:08:30,924 --> 00:08:33,358
Stop this.

141
00:08:33,426 --> 00:08:35,394
[ Chuckling ]
Honestly.

142
00:08:35,462 --> 00:08:37,657
Excuse me, I need to talk to you
for a second, Chancellor.

143
00:08:37,731 --> 00:08:38,891
I need to talk to you too.

144
00:08:38,965 --> 00:08:42,264
Maybe you could help me take these
coats to the upstairs guest room.

145
00:08:42,335 --> 00:08:45,532
I'd be happy to if I knew where
the upstairs guest room was.

146
00:08:45,605 --> 00:08:47,004
I could show you.

147
00:08:47,073 --> 00:08:49,837
- [ Continues Barking ]
- Terry.

148
00:08:49,909 --> 00:08:52,441
Yeah. Oh, yeah.
We'll make ourselves at home.

149
00:08:52,575 --> 00:08:54,839
We'll let Poe show us around.
Thanks.

150
00:09:02,785 --> 00:09:05,481
That's new, isn't it?

151
00:09:05,554 --> 00:09:08,079
Yeah, Walter just
got it back from the framer.

152
00:09:10,359 --> 00:09:12,691
You first.

153
00:09:14,430 --> 00:09:16,660
- This morning--
- I'm pregnant.

154
00:09:22,605 --> 00:09:24,539
I'm sure.

155
00:09:30,512 --> 00:09:34,278
Well, that's--
That's very surprising.

156
00:09:36,652 --> 00:09:39,416
Does Walter know that, uh--

157
00:09:39,488 --> 00:09:42,924
I think Walter would find this
a little more than surprising.

158
00:09:52,735 --> 00:09:55,727
Emily left me this morning.

159
00:09:55,804 --> 00:09:57,897
She's left before.

160
00:09:57,973 --> 00:10:01,409
She's left the room before,
but she's always come back.

161
00:10:05,214 --> 00:10:07,148
So.

162
00:10:09,084 --> 00:10:11,780
I guess we just divorce
our spouses, marry each other...

163
00:10:11,854 --> 00:10:14,448
and have this baby, right?

164
00:10:14,523 --> 00:10:16,457
Simple.

165
00:10:16,525 --> 00:10:18,857
Yeah, right. Simple.

166
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:27,498
Is that Cristalle?

167
00:10:27,569 --> 00:10:30,037
- Mm-hmm.
- Oh, God.

168
00:10:30,105 --> 00:10:33,632
I wear the same scent
as a transvestite.

169
00:10:33,709 --> 00:10:35,643
She is a transvestite,
isn't she?

170
00:10:35,711 --> 00:10:38,373
If she's not now,
Terry'll make sure she is...

171
00:10:38,447 --> 00:10:40,438
by the end of the evening.

172
00:10:40,516 --> 00:10:43,144
Has he asked you
about the book yet?

173
00:10:43,218 --> 00:10:45,243
Yes.

174
00:10:45,320 --> 00:10:47,254
And?

175
00:10:48,590 --> 00:10:51,457
Are you gonna tell him?

176
00:10:51,527 --> 00:10:56,726
No. Maybe. I don't know
what I'm gonna do.

177
00:10:56,799 --> 00:10:59,495
Me either.

178
00:10:59,635 --> 00:11:01,535
- [ Sniffing ]
- [Man ]DiMaggio 's record...

179
00:11:01,603 --> 00:11:03,537
for hits in consecutive games...

180
00:11:03,605 --> 00:11:05,835
is probably the most impressive
feat in all of sports...

181
00:11:05,908 --> 00:11:07,933
and in my opinion,
will never be broken.

182
00:11:08,010 --> 00:11:10,808
- Come here, big guy.
- His condition's so sad.

183
00:11:10,879 --> 00:11:13,143
Yes, but even blind,
he still gets around.

184
00:11:13,215 --> 00:11:16,810
[Narrating]
I don't drink normally...

185
00:11:16,885 --> 00:11:20,480
but this was turning out to be
one fucked-up day.

186
00:11:20,556 --> 00:11:24,788
And now I found myself in close
proximity to Sara 's husband...

187
00:11:24,860 --> 00:11:27,385
and his dog, Poe.

188
00:11:27,463 --> 00:11:30,023
-Walter, I see you've met my friend.
-Oh, yes. She's charming.

189
00:11:30,099 --> 00:11:32,499
Despite his much-vaunted
Harvard education...

190
00:11:32,568 --> 00:11:36,299
Dr. Walter Gaskell didn't have
a clue about his wife and me.

191
00:11:36,371 --> 00:11:39,169
Simply put, Di Maggio represented--
metaphorically speaking, of course--

192
00:11:39,241 --> 00:11:41,175
the husband as slugger.

193
00:11:41,243 --> 00:11:43,711
[Narrating]Poe had been
on to me since day one.

194
00:11:43,779 --> 00:11:46,339
- [ Poe Growling ]
- In fact, I personally believe...

195
00:11:46,415 --> 00:11:50,909
that every woman in some way
desires to be Marilyn Monroe.

196
00:11:50,986 --> 00:11:53,420
Oh, I couldn't agree more.

197
00:11:53,489 --> 00:11:56,720
[Man ] I've had a lot
of successes over the years.

198
00:11:56,792 --> 00:12:00,193
[Narrating]
Q. Q was rich.

199
00:12:00,262 --> 00:12:02,230
Q was famous.

200
00:12:02,297 --> 00:12:05,061
Q completed a novel
every 18 months.

201
00:12:05,134 --> 00:12:07,102
I hated him.

202
00:12:07,169 --> 00:12:09,399
...finest work vanished
in less than five.

203
00:12:09,471 --> 00:12:12,269
So I find myself conflicted.

204
00:12:12,341 --> 00:12:15,868
Ask him if he's conflicted
about his house in the Hamptons.

205
00:12:15,944 --> 00:12:18,913
- Grady.
- Well, Professor.

206
00:12:18,981 --> 00:12:20,278
Q. for your information...

207
00:12:20,349 --> 00:12:22,214
Hannah already has
two stories published...

208
00:12:22,284 --> 00:12:26,687
in The Paris Review, so you
better dust off your "A " material.

209
00:12:26,755 --> 00:12:29,986
You didn't tell me
you were a writer.

210
00:12:30,058 --> 00:12:31,548
You didn't ask.

211
00:12:31,627 --> 00:12:33,561
[Man ]How did you feel
about the adaptation?

212
00:12:33,629 --> 00:12:35,654
I thought it was more literary
than cinematic.

213
00:12:35,731 --> 00:12:36,891
[Man ]
Grady.

214
00:12:36,965 --> 00:12:39,263
Douglas Triddley, Amherst.

215
00:12:39,334 --> 00:12:40,528
I've had Arsonist 's Daughter...

216
00:12:40,602 --> 00:12:43,070
on my graduate-studies syllabus
three years running.

217
00:12:43,138 --> 00:12:45,572
No wonder it's still in print.

218
00:12:47,142 --> 00:12:49,076
[ Woman ]Long time since
Arsonist's Daughter.

219
00:13:08,163 --> 00:13:10,097
[ Walter]
There you are.

220
00:13:10,165 --> 00:13:15,626
I could have sworn I had a bottle
of 1975 Lafite Rothschild for Q.

221
00:13:15,704 --> 00:13:17,695
Given that he's going to be
addressing 500 people...

222
00:13:17,773 --> 00:13:19,206
in less than an hour--

223
00:13:19,274 --> 00:13:21,970
- You want to keep Q happy.
- If he's happy, I'm happy.

224
00:13:28,483 --> 00:13:31,008
[ Twig Snaps]

225
00:13:42,931 --> 00:13:45,092
James?

226
00:13:49,071 --> 00:13:52,006
It's fake.
It was my mother's.

227
00:13:52,074 --> 00:13:55,009
She won it in a penny arcade
in Baltimore...

228
00:13:55,077 --> 00:13:57,136
when she went
to Catholic school.

229
00:13:58,347 --> 00:14:01,009
Well, that's very convincing.

230
00:14:01,083 --> 00:14:03,847
I used to shoot
these little paper caps...

231
00:14:03,919 --> 00:14:06,353
but they don't make them anymore,
the caps.

232
00:14:06,421 --> 00:14:10,118
It's just for good luck, you know?
Some people carry rabbit's feet.

233
00:14:10,192 --> 00:14:12,683
You carry firearms.

234
00:14:14,529 --> 00:14:18,556
No, thank you. I don't like
to lose control of my emotions.

235
00:14:20,302 --> 00:14:23,237
I'm not supposed to be here,
in case you're wondering.

236
00:14:23,305 --> 00:14:26,035
But the other night I was out
with Hannah at the movies...

237
00:14:26,108 --> 00:14:30,670
and she asked me since she was
coming, so I ended up coming too.

238
00:14:30,746 --> 00:14:32,907
You and, uh, Hannah,
you're seeing each other?

239
00:14:32,981 --> 00:14:35,973
- No! What gave you that idea?
-James, relax.

240
00:14:36,051 --> 00:14:38,383
I'm not her father.
I just rent her a room.

241
00:14:38,453 --> 00:14:41,388
She likes old movies like I do,
that's all.

242
00:14:41,456 --> 00:14:44,220
- What's the movie you guys saw?
- Son of Fury...

243
00:14:44,293 --> 00:14:46,693
with Tyrone Power
and Frances Farmer.

244
00:14:47,763 --> 00:14:50,493
She went crazy,
Frances Farmer.

245
00:14:50,565 --> 00:14:53,056
So did Gene Tierney.
She's in it too.

246
00:14:54,202 --> 00:14:56,568
- Sounds like a good one.
- It wasn't bad.

247
00:14:59,775 --> 00:15:02,300
You're not like
my other teachers, Prof. Tripp.

248
00:15:02,377 --> 00:15:05,437
You're not like
my other students, James.

249
00:15:05,514 --> 00:15:07,914
Look, James...

250
00:15:07,983 --> 00:15:11,612
about this afternoon
in workshop, I'm sorry.

251
00:15:11,687 --> 00:15:13,985
I think I let things
get a little out of hand.

252
00:15:14,056 --> 00:15:15,045
They really hated it.

253
00:15:15,123 --> 00:15:17,591
I think they hated it more
than any of the other ones.

254
00:15:17,659 --> 00:15:19,354
- Well--
- Doesn't matter.

255
00:15:19,428 --> 00:15:21,589
It only took me
an hour to write.

256
00:15:21,663 --> 00:15:25,121
Really? That's remarkable.

257
00:15:25,200 --> 00:15:27,691
I have trouble sleeping.

258
00:15:27,769 --> 00:15:31,899
While I'm lying in bed,
I figure them out, the stories.

259
00:15:33,675 --> 00:15:37,805
- You cold, James?
- Oh, a little.

260
00:15:37,879 --> 00:15:40,279
Why don 't we go inside?

261
00:15:40,349 --> 00:15:42,283
It's colder in there.

262
00:15:42,351 --> 00:15:45,411
[ Chuckles ]
I guess you're right.

263
00:15:45,487 --> 00:15:48,547
Actually, I saw the greenhouse.

264
00:15:48,623 --> 00:15:51,922
I thought I'd come outside and take
a look at it. It looks like heaven.

265
00:15:53,862 --> 00:15:56,729
- Looks like heaven?
- I saw a movie once.

266
00:15:56,798 --> 00:16:00,757
Part of it took place in heaven.
Everyone wore white.

267
00:16:00,836 --> 00:16:03,327
Lived in crystal houses
like that.

268
00:16:04,806 --> 00:16:06,933
I really should be going.

269
00:16:08,410 --> 00:16:12,369
- Good-bye, Prof. Tripp.
- Hey, James.

270
00:16:12,447 --> 00:16:14,881
James, don't go. No.

271
00:16:14,950 --> 00:16:17,111
There's something
I want you to see.

272
00:16:18,553 --> 00:16:22,580
- I'll miss my bus.
- It's worth it.

273
00:16:22,657 --> 00:16:24,591
Trust me.

274
00:16:29,164 --> 00:16:31,248
[Hannah ]
Let me help you with that.

275
00:16:31,382 --> 00:16:33,850
Thank you, dear.
Thank you.

276
00:16:33,917 --> 00:16:36,647
Come on.

277
00:16:39,390 --> 00:16:42,587
[Hannah ]Hey, you two.
James, are you riding with me?

278
00:16:42,659 --> 00:16:46,288
- No, I'm going home--
- No, he's going with me.

279
00:16:46,363 --> 00:16:49,526
Why don't you take Crabtree
and his friend? All right?

280
00:16:49,600 --> 00:16:52,296
- All right.
- Where are they anyway?

281
00:16:52,369 --> 00:16:54,701
Here we are.

282
00:16:54,772 --> 00:16:58,765
Hmm. Well, hello there.

283
00:16:58,842 --> 00:17:02,642
James, this is my editor,
Terry Crabtree.

284
00:17:02,713 --> 00:17:03,702
James.

285
00:17:03,781 --> 00:17:05,476
[Hannah ]James'll know
about George Sanders.

286
00:17:05,549 --> 00:17:07,779
- George Sanders?
- Mr. Crabtree was saying...

287
00:17:07,851 --> 00:17:10,843
how George Sanders killed himself,
only he couldn't remember how.

288
00:17:10,921 --> 00:17:15,381
Pills. April 25, 1 972,
in a Costa Brava hotel room.

289
00:17:15,459 --> 00:17:17,620
- How comprehensive of you.
- [Hannah ]James is amazing.

290
00:17:17,694 --> 00:17:21,289
He knows all the movie suicides.
Go ahead, James. Tell him.

291
00:17:21,365 --> 00:17:23,993
- There are so many.
- Well, just a few. The big ones.

292
00:17:24,067 --> 00:17:29,027
Pier Angeli, 1971 or '72,
also pills.

293
00:17:29,106 --> 00:17:31,597
Donald " Red " Barry,
shot himself in 1 980.

294
00:17:31,675 --> 00:17:33,939
Charles Boyer,
1978, pills again.

295
00:17:34,011 --> 00:17:38,004
Charles Butterworth, 1946,
I think. In a car.

296
00:17:38,081 --> 00:17:42,017
Supposedly, it was an accident,
but, you know, he was distraught.

297
00:17:42,085 --> 00:17:46,385
Dorothy Dandridge, pills, 1965.
Albert Dekker, 1968.

298
00:17:46,457 --> 00:17:47,446
He hung himself.

299
00:17:47,524 --> 00:17:49,492
He wrote his suicide note
in lipstick on his stomach.

300
00:17:49,560 --> 00:17:52,051
William lnge,
carbon monoxide, 1973.

301
00:17:52,129 --> 00:17:54,495
Carole Landis, pills again.
I forget when.

302
00:17:54,565 --> 00:17:57,432
George Reeves,
"Superman" on TV, shot himself.

303
00:17:57,501 --> 00:18:00,402
Jean Seberg, pills,
of course, 1 979.

304
00:18:00,471 --> 00:18:03,599
Everett Sloane--
he was good-- pills.

305
00:18:03,674 --> 00:18:06,541
Margaret Sulla van, pills.
Lupe Velez, a lot of pills.

306
00:18:06,610 --> 00:18:09,511
Gig Young, he shot himself
and his wife in 1 978.

307
00:18:09,580 --> 00:18:11,241
There are tons more.

308
00:18:11,315 --> 00:18:14,148
- I haven't heard of half of them.
- You did them alphabetically.

309
00:18:14,218 --> 00:18:16,209
It's just how my bra in works,
I guess.

310
00:18:16,286 --> 00:18:17,446
Fascinating.

311
00:18:17,521 --> 00:18:19,182
Come out with us
after the lecture.

312
00:18:19,256 --> 00:18:21,247
There's this place
I always get Tripp to take me.

313
00:18:21,325 --> 00:18:23,793
-Actually, I just want to go home.
-Don 't be silly.

314
00:18:23,861 --> 00:18:26,557
No one your age
just wants to go home.

315
00:18:26,630 --> 00:18:30,396
Besides, faculty will be present.
Just consider it a field trip.

316
00:18:52,055 --> 00:18:53,989
[James]
ls that really it?

317
00:18:55,425 --> 00:18:57,655
That's really it.

318
00:18:57,728 --> 00:19:00,390
The one she wore
on her wedding day.

319
00:19:00,464 --> 00:19:02,591
So I'm told.

320
00:19:04,601 --> 00:19:07,832
- Go ahead.
- Really?

321
00:19:07,905 --> 00:19:09,873
Really.

322
00:19:22,853 --> 00:19:24,912
She was small.

323
00:19:24,988 --> 00:19:27,081
Most people don't know that.

324
00:19:29,159 --> 00:19:31,650
The shoulders
are so small.

325
00:19:35,198 --> 00:19:37,598
It looks so perfect.

326
00:19:38,835 --> 00:19:42,100
I bet it's the only time
she wore it.

327
00:19:42,172 --> 00:19:44,106
That day.

328
00:19:44,174 --> 00:19:48,668
She must have felt so happy.

329
00:19:51,748 --> 00:19:56,845
- Must've cost Dr. Gaskell a lot.
- I guess.

330
00:19:56,920 --> 00:19:59,320
He also never tells Sara
the truth...

331
00:19:59,389 --> 00:20:02,017
about how much
he pays for these things.

332
00:20:02,092 --> 00:20:05,186
You're really good friends
with the chancellor, aren't you?

333
00:20:07,931 --> 00:20:10,729
Pretty good.

334
00:20:10,801 --> 00:20:14,328
I'm friends
with her husband too.

335
00:20:14,404 --> 00:20:17,464
I guess you must be if you know
the combination to his closet...

336
00:20:17,541 --> 00:20:20,669
and he doesn't mind you being
in here in their bedroom.

337
00:20:22,746 --> 00:20:24,873
- Right.
- [Door Closing]

338
00:20:24,948 --> 00:20:27,712
[People Chattering]

339
00:20:35,292 --> 00:20:36,919
[ Woman ]
Drive carefully.

340
00:20:36,994 --> 00:20:39,724
Stick close
to me in case it gets slippery.

341
00:20:39,796 --> 00:20:43,095
We better skedaddle.
James--

342
00:20:43,166 --> 00:20:45,896
[ Sniffling ]

343
00:20:51,942 --> 00:20:54,877
You all right, James?

344
00:20:54,945 --> 00:20:59,143
Oh. I'm sorry,
Prof. Tripp.

345
00:21:01,151 --> 00:21:04,120
Maybe it's...

346
00:21:04,187 --> 00:21:07,315
seeing that jacket
that belonged to her.

347
00:21:09,393 --> 00:21:13,454
It just looks
really lonely...

348
00:21:13,530 --> 00:21:16,158
hanging there
in a closet.

349
00:21:18,935 --> 00:21:21,563
Maybe I'm just
a little sad tonight.

350
00:21:23,507 --> 00:21:27,102
I'm a little
sad tonight too, James.

351
00:21:27,177 --> 00:21:30,977
You mean, with your wife
leaving you and all?

352
00:21:36,153 --> 00:21:38,849
Hannah mentioned something
about it.

353
00:21:41,591 --> 00:21:45,925
Yeah, well,
it's complicated, James.

354
00:21:45,996 --> 00:21:48,123
I think we should go now.

355
00:21:54,671 --> 00:21:57,299
[Metal Jingling]

356
00:22:03,313 --> 00:22:06,339
[ Sniffing ]

357
00:22:06,416 --> 00:22:08,976
[ Growling ]

358
00:22:20,997 --> 00:22:23,295
[ Gasps ]
Easy, easy.

359
00:22:23,366 --> 00:22:26,995
He's a good boy, Poe.
Poe's a good boy. Easy, Poe.

360
00:22:27,070 --> 00:22:30,198
Easy. Good dog.

361
00:22:30,273 --> 00:22:32,798
- [ Barking ]
- [ Yelling ]

362
00:22:34,411 --> 00:22:36,436
Jesus Christ!
Get off!

363
00:22:41,118 --> 00:22:43,052
[ Gunshots ]

364
00:22:55,766 --> 00:22:57,825
Shit, James.

365
00:22:57,901 --> 00:22:59,994
You shot Dr. Gaskell's dog.

366
00:23:02,939 --> 00:23:05,237
But l--
I had to, didn't l?

367
00:23:05,308 --> 00:23:07,276
You could've
pulled him off me.

368
00:23:07,344 --> 00:23:11,212
No, the dog was crazy, Prof. Tripp.
The dog was attacking you!

369
00:23:11,281 --> 00:23:14,842
Calm down, James.
Don't freak out, all right?

370
00:23:18,052 --> 00:23:21,579
Okay. All right.
Do you have a mirror?

371
00:23:21,656 --> 00:23:24,648
It's the best way to see
if someone's still breathing.

372
00:23:24,725 --> 00:23:27,353
The dog is dead, James.
Believe me.

373
00:23:27,428 --> 00:23:30,488
I know a dead dog
when I see one.

374
00:23:32,433 --> 00:23:36,631
- Oh, shit.
- What are we supposed to do now?

375
00:23:39,040 --> 00:23:43,033
First, you're gonna give me
that little cap gun of yours.

376
00:23:43,110 --> 00:23:45,078
Come on.

377
00:23:49,450 --> 00:23:54,149
Prof. Tripp,
what are we gonna do with...

378
00:23:54,221 --> 00:23:56,382
it?

379
00:23:56,457 --> 00:23:59,790
[ Sighs ] I don't know.
I'm still trying to figure out...

380
00:23:59,860 --> 00:24:02,385
how to tell the chancellor
that I murdered her husband's dog.

381
00:24:02,463 --> 00:24:04,761
- You?
- Trust me, James.

382
00:24:04,832 --> 00:24:06,663
When the family pet's
been assassinated...

383
00:24:06,734 --> 00:24:08,497
the owner
does not want to hear...

384
00:24:08,569 --> 00:24:10,594
that one of her students
was the triggerman.

385
00:24:10,671 --> 00:24:13,538
Does she wanna hear
it was one of her professors?

386
00:24:17,144 --> 00:24:19,078
I've got tenure.

387
00:24:21,082 --> 00:24:23,016
Hang on.

388
00:24:31,092 --> 00:24:33,890
It's still warm.

389
00:24:33,961 --> 00:24:35,895
Let's try feet first.

390
00:24:46,073 --> 00:24:49,736
Yuck! That is a big trunk.

391
00:24:49,810 --> 00:24:52,108
It holds a tuba, a suitcase...

392
00:24:52,179 --> 00:24:54,704
a dead dog and a garment bag
almost perfectly.

393
00:24:54,782 --> 00:24:57,649
Yep. That's just what they
used to say in the ads.

394
00:24:57,718 --> 00:24:59,777
Come on, Crabtree.
I know you're holding.

395
00:24:59,854 --> 00:25:01,685
Whose tuba is that anyway?

396
00:25:01,756 --> 00:25:04,384
-Miss Sloviak's.
-Can I ask you something about her?

397
00:25:04,458 --> 00:25:07,757
- Yes, she is.
- So is your friend Crabtree--

398
00:25:07,828 --> 00:25:09,762
Is he-- Is he gay?

399
00:25:09,830 --> 00:25:12,060
Most of the time he is, James.
Some of the time he isn't.

400
00:25:12,133 --> 00:25:15,500
What do we have here?

401
00:25:15,569 --> 00:25:17,503
This looks like--

402
00:25:18,706 --> 00:25:20,674
That's our old friend
Mr. Codeine.

403
00:25:20,741 --> 00:25:24,142
That should take the old pinch
out of the ankle. You want one?

404
00:25:25,379 --> 00:25:28,576
- No, thanks. I'm fine without them.
- Right.

405
00:25:28,649 --> 00:25:30,844
That's why you were standing
in the chancellor's backyard ...

406
00:25:30,918 --> 00:25:32,408
spinning that cap gun of yours.

407
00:25:32,486 --> 00:25:35,785
You're fine. Yeah, you're just
as fit as a fucking fiddle.

408
00:25:48,269 --> 00:25:51,830
[ Sighs ] I'm sorry, James.
I'm sorry I said that.

409
00:26:09,957 --> 00:26:12,391
How about we try that again?

410
00:26:17,098 --> 00:26:19,066
[ Walter] It is
a great pleasure to introduce...

411
00:26:19,133 --> 00:26:21,533
best-selling author
Quentin Morewood...

412
00:26:21,602 --> 00:26:24,799
known to his friends
simply as Q.

413
00:26:24,872 --> 00:26:26,965
[ Applauding ]

414
00:26:36,317 --> 00:26:38,251
[Applause Subsides]

415
00:26:44,091 --> 00:26:47,993
I... am a writer.

416
00:26:48,062 --> 00:26:51,156
[ Applauding ]

417
00:26:51,232 --> 00:26:54,497
As a writer, you learn that
everyone you meet has a story.

418
00:26:54,568 --> 00:26:57,036
Every bartender,
every taxi driver...

419
00:26:57,104 --> 00:27:01,234
has an idea that would make
a great book.

420
00:27:01,308 --> 00:27:03,435
Presumably
each of you has an idea.

421
00:27:03,511 --> 00:27:06,309
But how do you get
from there to here?

422
00:27:06,380 --> 00:27:09,372
What is the bridge from
the water's edge of inspiration...

423
00:27:09,450 --> 00:27:12,078
to the far shore
of accomplishment?

424
00:27:12,153 --> 00:27:15,247
[ Laughing ]

425
00:27:24,765 --> 00:27:27,393
Faith.

426
00:27:27,468 --> 00:27:31,802
Faith that your story
is worth the telling.

427
00:27:31,872 --> 00:27:36,241
Faith that you have
the wherewithal to tell it.

428
00:27:36,310 --> 00:27:40,406
And faith that the carefully woven
structure that you create...

429
00:27:40,481 --> 00:27:43,348
won 't collapse beneath you.

430
00:27:43,417 --> 00:27:46,147
And faith that when you
get to the other side...

431
00:27:46,220 --> 00:27:48,154
there will be someone waiting...

432
00:27:48,222 --> 00:27:50,486
who gives a damn
about the tale you have to tell.

433
00:27:50,558 --> 00:27:53,049
- I'll be back in a minute.
- Like Whitman, I admit...

434
00:27:53,127 --> 00:27:55,220
I worship at the shrine
of formal construction.

435
00:27:55,296 --> 00:27:59,960
But like Conrad, I confess that
I have a secret sharer in my work.

436
00:28:00,034 --> 00:28:03,595
My double, my other self.

437
00:28:03,671 --> 00:28:07,732
I am haunted by this
malignant, remorseless shadow--

438
00:28:07,808 --> 00:28:09,742
[Fading, lndistinct]

439
00:28:28,896 --> 00:28:30,830
Grady.

440
00:28:34,268 --> 00:28:36,202
Grady.

441
00:28:39,173 --> 00:28:41,641
You had another one again,
didn't you?

442
00:28:43,310 --> 00:28:45,244
Is the thing--

443
00:28:46,814 --> 00:28:48,748
Is it over?

444
00:28:48,816 --> 00:28:52,217
Almost. Wanna sit up?

445
00:28:55,189 --> 00:28:57,123
[ Groaning ]

446
00:28:57,191 --> 00:28:59,386
What's wrong?

447
00:28:59,460 --> 00:29:03,157
Nothing, I just twisted--

448
00:29:05,065 --> 00:29:08,193
Sara, there's something
I've gotta tell you.

449
00:29:08,269 --> 00:29:10,237
Something hard .

450
00:29:12,806 --> 00:29:16,173
Stand up then. I'm too old for all
this rolling around on the floor.

451
00:29:16,243 --> 00:29:18,177
Give me a hand?

452
00:29:29,723 --> 00:29:31,953
- Well, this evening--
- Don't.

453
00:29:32,026 --> 00:29:33,960
I know what you're gonna say.

454
00:29:34,028 --> 00:29:36,588
I don't think you do know
what I'm gonna say, Sara.

455
00:29:36,664 --> 00:29:39,428
You love Emily. Of course you love
Emily. She's young, beautiful.

456
00:29:39,500 --> 00:29:42,094
She's your wife.
You have to stay with her.

457
00:29:42,169 --> 00:29:45,502
B-But I don't have a choice.
Emily left me.

458
00:29:45,572 --> 00:29:50,134
She'll come back.
That's why I'm going to--

459
00:29:50,210 --> 00:29:52,144
[ Softly ]
To not have this baby.

460
00:29:55,983 --> 00:29:57,951
You're not gonna have it?

461
00:29:59,920 --> 00:30:04,789
No, there's no way. I mean,
don't you think there's no way?

462
00:30:11,198 --> 00:30:15,259
Well, I don't see any,
but I know what it means to you.

463
00:30:15,336 --> 00:30:16,564
No, you don't.

464
00:30:16,637 --> 00:30:20,004
And fuck you for saying you do,
for saying that there's no way.

465
00:30:20,074 --> 00:30:22,702
Because there could
be a way, Grady.

466
00:30:22,776 --> 00:30:25,540
[Applause, Distant]

467
00:30:25,612 --> 00:30:28,137
They must be finishing.
We should go.

468
00:30:34,655 --> 00:30:36,623
Whose gun is that?

469
00:30:38,158 --> 00:30:40,558
A souvenir
from Baltimore.

470
00:30:40,627 --> 00:30:42,618
It's heavy. Smells like--
[ Sniffing ]

471
00:30:42,696 --> 00:30:44,789
- Gunpowder.
- Caps.

472
00:30:56,577 --> 00:30:58,772
Pow.

473
00:31:02,049 --> 00:31:03,983
You got me.

474
00:31:06,520 --> 00:31:08,647
I love you, Grady.

475
00:31:17,598 --> 00:31:19,964
The doors made so much noise.

476
00:31:20,034 --> 00:31:22,696
It was so embarrassing.
They had to carry him out.

477
00:31:22,770 --> 00:31:24,704
- Is he all right?
- He's fine. He's narrating.

478
00:31:24,772 --> 00:31:27,138
They were going
to the men's room...

479
00:31:27,207 --> 00:31:29,835
but would they
make it in time?

480
00:31:29,910 --> 00:31:33,038
Terry Crabtree
and James Leer.

481
00:31:33,113 --> 00:31:36,947
Leave it to you to make
that mistake. Wait here.

482
00:31:44,358 --> 00:31:47,225
- I need a ride.
- I'm your man.

483
00:31:57,873 --> 00:31:59,807
There's an explanation.

484
00:31:59,875 --> 00:32:04,107
Couldn't he have just thrown
a shoe at the poor thing?

485
